Issues #19647, #22604 and #29071 centered around how slow NumPy's einsum is compared to other libraries. The last issue to use BLAS even when `optimize=False` became a [branch](https://github.com/lysnikolaou/numpy/tree/use-blas-even-if-nooptimize) but did not become a PR because the heuristics proved difficult to tune.

Rather than try to guess what is better, perhaps we could allow the user to force using BLAS with a new kwarg? This would be "safe" in terms of performance as it would allow the user to choose. It seems #23513 will speed up the `optimize=True` case, but the kwarg would allow users of intermediate-sized arrays to get BLAS threading speedups even when using `optimize=False`.

@jcmgray, as someone who has put a lot of effort into einsum, would there be use-cases where `optimize=False, use_blas=True` could improve performance over `optimize=True`?

### Proposed new feature or change:

Hi, I was optimizing some 3D image code and found that this line was slow due to the input images being all in F-order.

```python
output = np.zeros([512,512,512], dtype=np.uint32, order="F")
output[slices][binary_image] = some_integer
```

In the above sample, `binary_image` is exactly matched to the size of slices (`(slice,slice,slice)`). `binary_image` is in F order as well as output. When I changed them to C order, the code ran much faster. However, my input images are in F order and are often under tight memory constraints. I ended up writing pybind11 code to perform this operation:

```python
      # This function call is equivalent to:
      # output[slices][binary_image] = mapping[label]
      # 
      # It avoids an Fortran vs C order impedance mismatch
      # that was causing a large performance hit.
      fastmorphops.draw_with_mask_f_order(
        output, 
        int(slices[0].start), int(slices[0].stop),
        int(slices[1].start), int(slices[1].stop),
        int(slices[2].start), int(slices[2].stop),
        binary_image,
        mapping[label]
      )
```

Which has the following straightforward implementation though I have the luxury of handling known contiguous arrays.

```cpp
template <typename T>
void draw_with_mask_f_order(
	const py::array_t<T> &output,
	const uint64_t x_start, const uint64_t x_end,
	const uint64_t y_start, const uint64_t y_end,
	const uint64_t z_start, const uint64_t z_end,
	const py::array_t<bool>& binary_image,
	const int64_t value
) {
	const uint64_t sx = output.shape()[0];
	const uint64_t sy = output.shape()[1];

    auto buf = output.request();  // buffer info
    auto ptr = static_cast<T*>(buf.ptr);

    auto binary_buf = binary_image.request();
    const bool* bool_ptr = static_cast<const bool*>(binary_buf.ptr);

    uint64_t i = 0;
	for (uint64_t z = z_start; z < z_end; z++) {
		for (uint64_t y = y_start; y < y_end; y++) {
			for (uint64_t x = x_start; x < x_end; x++, i++) {
				uint64_t loc = x + sx * (y + sy * z);
				if (bool_ptr[i]) {
					ptr[loc] = value;
				}
			}
		}
	}
}
```

It's not a huge deal, but it would be nice if the standard numpy code adjusted for the input types if both the source and destination array matched in layout.

You can see this code in context here:
https://github.com/seung-lab/fastmorph/blob/1.8.0/fastmorph/__init__.py#L404-L416
